    "creation_date" : 1353280284,
    "answer_id" : 13445607,
    "question_id" : 3110547,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>org.apache.commons.lang3.tuple.Pair</code> implements <code>java.util.Map.Entry</code> and can also be used standalone.</p>\n\n<p>Also as others mentioned Guava's <code>com.google.common.collect.Maps.immutableEntry(K, V)</code> does the trick.</p>\n\n<p>I prefer <code>Pair</code> for its fluent <code>Pair.of(L, R)</code> syntax.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3641293,
      "reputation" : 139,
      "user_id" : 3035296,
      "user_type" : "unregistered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/efa4d45cc93acc9c68c7dad9b45cfdb7?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "tanghao",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3035296/tanghao"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 13,
    "last_activity_date" : 1385451631,
    "last_edit_date" : 1385451631,
    "creation_date" : 1385450391,
    "answer_id" : 20210795,
    "question_id" : 3110547,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Why <code>Map.Entry</code>? I guess something like a key-value pair is fit for the case.</p>\n\n<p>Use <code>java.util.AbstractMap.SimpleImmutableEntry</code> or <code>java.util.AbstractMap.SimpleEntry</code></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 199671,
      "reputation" : 155307,
      "user_id" : 445131,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 89,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/2b4pE.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Eric Leschinski",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/445131/eric-leschinski"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 37,
    "last_activity_date" : 1443307618,
    "creation_date" : 1443307618,
    "answer_id" : 32802784,
    "question_id" : 3110547,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><strong>Example of AbstractMap.SimpleEntry:</strong></p>\n\n<pre><code>import java.util.Map; \nimport java.util.AbstractMap;\nimport java.util.AbstractMap.SimpleEntry;\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><strong>Instantiate:</strong></p>\n\n<pre><code>ArrayList&lt;Map.Entry&lt;Integer, Integer&gt;&gt; arr = \n    new ArrayList&lt;Map.Entry&lt;Integer, Integer&gt;&gt;();\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><strong>Add rows:</strong></p>\n\n<pre><code>arr.add(new AbstractMap.SimpleEntry(2, 3));\narr.add(new AbstractMap.SimpleEntry(20, 30));\narr.add(new AbstractMap.SimpleEntry(2, 4));\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><strong>Fetch rows:</strong></p>\n\n<pre><code>System.out.println(arr.get(0).getKey());\nSystem.out.println(arr.get(0).getValue());\nSystem.out.println(arr.get(1).getKey());\nSystem.out.println(arr.get(1).getValue());\nSystem.out.println(arr.get(2).getKey());\nSystem.out.println(arr.get(2).getValue());\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><strong>Should print:</strong></p>\n\n<pre><code>2\n3\n20\n30\n2\n4\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>It's good for defining edges of graph structures.  Like the ones between neurons in your head.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "user_type" : "does_not_exist",
      "display_name" : "anon"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1468946656,
    "creation_date" : 1468946656,
    "answer_id" : 38464187,
    "question_id" : 3110547,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you are using Clojure, you have another option:</p>\n\n<pre><code>(defn map-entry\n  [k v]\n  (clojure.lang.MapEntry/create k v))\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
