      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "It looks like Java provides basic features like this well after other languages do. Until then, we have to use clunky methods like this <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/3110563/6648326\">stackoverflow.com/a/3110563/6648326</a>."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 8906759,
        "reputation" : 2390,
        "user_id" : 6648326,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 71,
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/zaG25.jpg?s=256",
        "display_name" : "MasterJoe",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6648326/masterjoe"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 1,
      "creation_date" : 1595791898,
      "post_id" : 52426752,
      "comment_id" : 111589932,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "Its great that we can create an Entry. But there is no easy way to add an entry to a map. Refer - <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/39441096/how-to-put-an-entry-into-a-map\" title=\"how to put an entry into a map\">stackoverflow.com/questions/39441096/&hellip;</a> ? I don&#39;t want to keep extracting data from the Entry and then put it into a map. I want the map to do the extraction for me."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 9531412,
        "reputation" : 2925,
        "user_id" : 7082956,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/99d1d4ee28260791f03b53f13a3bf6b2?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
        "display_name" : "Valerij Dobler",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7082956/valerij-dobler"
      },
      "reply_to_user" : {
        "account_id" : 8906759,
        "reputation" : 2390,
        "user_id" : 6648326,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 71,
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/zaG25.jpg?s=256",
        "display_name" : "MasterJoe",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6648326/masterjoe"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1618846033,
      "post_id" : 52426752,
      "comment_id" : 118720065,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "@MasterJoe you can just use <code>Map.of(&quot;key1&quot;, &quot;value1&quot;, &quot;key2&quot;, &quot;value2&quot;)</code> to add entries to a map. Or if you have an existing map: <code>map.put(entry.getKey(), entry.getValue())</code>"
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2269593,
      "reputation" : 45235,
      "user_id" : 1997376,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 100,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/3AtSv.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Nicolas Filotto",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1997376/nicolas-filotto"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 234,
    "last_activity_date" : 1562935700,
    "last_edit_date" : 1562935700,
    "creation_date" : 1537451482,
    "answer_id" : 52426752,
    "question_id" : 3110547,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Starting from <strong>Java 9,</strong> there is a new utility method allowing to create an immutable entry which is <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/9/docs/api/java/util/Map.html#entry-K-V-\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>Map#entry(Object, Object)</code></a>. </p>\n\n<p>Here is a simple example:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Entry&lt;String, String&gt; entry = Map.entry(\"foo\", \"bar\");\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>As it is immutable, calling <code>setValue</code> will throw an <code>UnsupportedOperationException</code>. The other limitations are the fact that it is not serializable and <code>null</code> as key or value is forbidden, if it is not acceptable for you, you will need to use <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/9/docs/api/java/util/AbstractMap.SimpleImmutableEntry.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>AbstractMap.SimpleImmutableEntry</code></a> or <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/9/docs/api/java/util/AbstractMap.SimpleEntry.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>AbstractMap.SimpleEntry</code></a> instead.</p>\n\n<p><strong>NB:</strong> If your need is to create directly a <code>Map</code> with 0 to up to 10 (key, value) pairs, you can instead use the methods of type <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/9/docs/api/java/util/Map.html#of-K-V-\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>Map.of(K key1, V value1, ...)</code></a>.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 13573704,
        "reputation" : 2254,
        "user_id" : 9791674,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4dbe72e332c3b0602092feab2d0bc53b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
        "display_name" : "Languoguang",
