      "post_id" : 79681262,
      "comment_id" : 140548623,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "The question&#39;s OP wants to be able to instantiate a tuple that can hold two values: &quot;I&#39;d like to create new item that similarly to Util.Map.Entry that will contain the structure key, value.&quot; .   I don&#39;t think he wants to create a Map.Entry object specifically (Java didn&#39;t have that ability in 2010, when the question was asked).  The Records class provides a concise &amp; modern solution for this."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 31180,
        "reputation" : 29752,
        "user_id" : 85421,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/kKvXH.gif?s=256",
        "display_name" : "user85421",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/85421/user85421"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 1,
      "creation_date" : 1751098154,
      "post_id" : 79681262,
      "comment_id" : 140549046,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "or maybe they want(ed) an instance that implements <code>Map.Entry</code> (&quot;<i>Does anyone know how to create a new generic key/value object for Map.Entry?</i>&quot;) -- ((by the way, not the best example having a class named &quot;Rectangle&quot; to hold a key-value pair))"
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3217817,
      "reputation" : 60,
      "user_id" : 2715997,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://graph.facebook.com/100001175657149/picture?type=large",
      "display_name" : "Apoorv Gupta",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2715997/apoorv-gupta"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : -1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1751068255,
    "last_edit_date" : 1751068255,
    "creation_date" : 1750980059,
    "answer_id" : 79681262,
    "question_id" : 3110547,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you are using Java 16 or later, you can define a Records class to hold a pair of values:</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>record Rectangle(double key, double value) { }\n</code></pre>\n<pre><code>Rectangle r = new Rectangle(4,5);\n\nYou can access the elements with\nRectangle::key() and Rectangle::value()\n\n\n\n\n\n\nJava Records are immutable, but they can be serialized and sorted by implementing appropriate interfaces\n</code></pre>\n"
  } ],
